<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-095 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Officials' Remarks on Forces in South Decried </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Officials' Remarks on Forces in South Decried </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1705052894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0517 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1705052894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Dangerous Anti-DPRK Outbursts of U.S. Warmaniacs" -- KCNA </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, May 17 (KCNA) -- The U.S. defense 
secretary, Perry, said recently that the United States was 
examining steps to shorten the time needed for the preparation 
of the dispatch of U.S. aircraft carriers to the Korean 
peninsula and increase the stockpile of ammunition of the U.S. 
Forces stationed in South Korea and Japan, reported THE 
WASHINGTON POST May 12. 
  Perry and other U.S. brasshats cried that "a war must be 
imagined", threatening "sanctions" against the DPRK, the paper 
said. 
  On the 14th of May, Woolsey, director of the U.S. Central 
Intelligence Agency, at a meeting held in Boston openly argued 
that the U.S. intelligence agents should be "infiltrated" into 
the DPRK "in the disguise of forwarding agents or seamen" over 
the "nuclear issue". 
  U.S. President Clinton in his recent interview with the U.S. 
CNN TV, taking issue with the fictitious "nuclear issue" of the 
DPRK, declared that "a decisive stand" would be taken in the 
U.S.- led international moves for a solution to it. 
  These facts prove that the United States is bringing the 
situation on the Korean peninsula to the brink of war, 
invariably pursuing the policy of stifling the DPRK. 

</TEXT>

