<F P=103> SK1405215994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 14 (KCNA) -- American professor of 
Chicago University Bruce Cumings said at an academic seminar on 
the theme of "nuclear war crisis in Asia" that the United States 
should strive to pull nuclear weapons out of South Korea with 
the responsibility for its introduction according to NEW KOREA 
TIMES, a paper of overseas Koreans. 
  It is, he said, for a political purpose to keep up the cold 
war in the Korean peninsula that the United States is putting 
pressure on North Korea while keeping itself from making an 
official utterance on the introduction of nuclear weapons in 
South Korea. 
  Criticising the one-sided press attitude of the American 
media gossiping about "nuclear suspicion" in North Korea, the 
professor said that for the elimination of nuclear arms in the 
Korean peninsula and its peaceful reunification, it is 
preferential to have a correct understanding of the starting of 
the June 25 war, the U.S.-South Korean military tieup, the South 
Korean authorities' attitude towards the North, etc. 
  It is proper for the United States to solve the "nuclear 
issue" by means of dialogue with North Korea, not by military 
means, he stressed. 

</TEXT>

