<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Korean, Tanzanian Youth Groups Issue Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Korean, Tanzanian Youth Groups Issue Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1505091094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0831 GMT 15 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1505091094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 15 (KCNA) -- The League of Socialist 
Working Youth of Korea [LSWYK] and the Tanzanian Youth Union 
[TYU] released a joint statement here on May 13. 
  According to the statement, officials of the Central 
Committee of the LSWYK and the members of the visiting 
delegation of the TYU led by General Secretary Sukuwa S. Sukuwa 
exchanged views on a series of matters. 
  The statement says: 
  The sides informed each other of their organizations' 
activities and exchanged views on the development of friendly 
relations between the two youth organizations, the current 
international situation and the development of the world youth 
and student movement. 
  The LSWYK noted with appreciation that the TYU has played an 
important role and conducted brisk activities to build a new 
independent society and consolidate the unity of the nation and 
the country under the leadership of the Revolutionary Party of 
Tanzania, maintaining the line of socialism and self-reliance. 
  The TYU highly estimated the fact that the LSWYK, united in 
one mind around the great leader of the Korean people Comrade 
Kim Il- song and the dear leader Comrade Kim Chong-il, has 
successfully discharged its mission and role in the struggle for 
defending the Workers' Party of Korea and confidently 
safeguarding and advancing the cause of socialism in the hard 
time when the imperialists continue anti-socialist, anti-DPRK 
moves. 
  The TYU bitterly denounced the United States and its 
satellites for deploying Patriot missiles in South Korea and 
rendering the situation of the Korean peninsula extremely 
strained, while threatening sanctions against the DPRK through 
the International Atomic Energy Agency and the United Nations 
under the pretext of "the nuclear issue," and urged them to 
promptly stop such moves. 
  The sides emphasized the need to support and closely 
cooperate with each other in the common struggle for the 
development of the world youth movement for solidarity against 
imperialism and for peace and friendship and the cause of 
socialism. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53008 </DOCNO>
