<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Signature Campaign for Solidarity Launched </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Signature Campaign for Solidarity Launched </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1405104194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1012 GMT 14 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1405104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 14 (KCNA) -- An international 
signature campaign and other extensive activities for solidarity 
with the Korean people have been launched upon the lapse of one 
year since the great leader President Kim Il-song published 
"10-point programme of the great unity of the whole nation for 
the reunification of the country." 
  More than 360 million people including heads of party, state 
and government and other political and public figures of India, 
Nepal, Syria, Egypt, Guinea, France, Austria, Peru, Nicaragua 
and many other countries and international and regional 
organizations signed the signature paper supporting the 10-point 
programme in April. And various forms of solidarity functions 
such as meeting, seminar and lecture were held and statements 
and appeals were issued. 
  The International Liaison Committee for the Reunification 
and 
Peace in Korea (Cilreco) published an appeal and a signature 
paper on the first anniversary of the publication of the 
10-point programme. 
  The appeal said the 10-point programme put forward by 
President Kim Il-song is a great programme for Korean 
reunification indicating a way for the Korean people to found 
the Democratic Confederal Republic of Koryo independently and 
called for an international signature campaign supporting it in 
all countries. 
  In response to the appeal, political parties and 
organizations of Ghana, Mali, Russia, the Czech Republic and 
many other countries formed committees for sponsoring and 
promoting the signature campaign supporting the 10-point 
programme. 
  The signature campaign is going on worldwide. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53012 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas095_c_94043" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-095 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Anniversary of Korea-Nepal Relations Marked </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Anniversary of Korea-Nepal Relations Marked </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1505090994 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0825 GMT 15 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1505090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 15 (KCNA) -- Papers here today 
dedicate articles to the 20th anniversary of the establishment 
of diplomatic relations between the Democratic People's Republic 
of Korea and the Kingdom of Nepal (May 15, 1974). 
  NODONG SINMUN says that over the past two decades, the 
friendly and cooperative relations between the two peoples have 
developed favourably, which has been conducive to the building 
of a new life in the two countries. 
  The paper further says: 
  Today the Nepalese people are working hard to defend the 
sovereignty and territorial integrity of the country and develop 
the national economy. 
  The Kingdom of Nepal is striving to strengthen international 
cooperation, maintaining an independent stand and the principle 
of the non-aligned movement in external relations. 
  The Korean people are sincerely rejoiced over the 
achievements made by the Nepalese people in the building of a 
new life. 
  Further developing the friendly and cooperative relations 
between Korea and Nepal is beneficial not only to the building 
of a new society in the two countries but also to the building 
of a new Asia independent and prospering. 
  MINJU CHOSON says the Korean people will as ever make 
strenuous efforts to develop friendship and cooperation with the 
Nepalese people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

