<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Burma </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on SRV Prime Minister's Visit Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on SRV Prime Minister's Visit Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Joint Communique Released </H4>

<F P=102> BK1505095894 Rangoon Radio Burma in Burmese 1330 GMT 14 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1505095894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rangoon Radio Burma </F>
<F P=105>  Burmese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A joint communique has been issued at the 
conclusion of the visit of Mr. Vo Van Kiet, prime minister of 
the Socialist Republic of Vietnam [SRV], to the Union of Myanmar 
[Burma]. The full text of the communique reads: 
  At the invitation of Senior General Than Shwe, prime 
minister 
of the Union of Myanmar, Mr. Vo Van Kiet, prime minister of the 
SRV, paid an official visit to the Union of Myanmar from 11 May 
to 14 May 1994. Prime Minister of the SRV and Madame Vo Van 
Kiet were accompanied by Minister of Foreign Affairs and Madame 
Nguyen Manh Cam; Mr. Tran Hoan, minister of culture and 
information; Mr. Nguyen Quang Ha, minister of forestry; 
Lieutenant General Nguyen Thoi Bung, vice minister of national 
defense; Mr. Doan Manh Giao, vice chairman of the Government 
Office; Mr. Tran Van Tuyen, vice minister of commerce; Mr. Ngo 
Thi Doan, vice minister of agriculture and food industry; Mr. 
Nguyen Thuong Bang, vice minister of heavy industry; Mr. Do 
Quang Trung, chairman of the Vietnam Tourism Administration; 
Mr. Luu Van An, chairman of the People's Committee of Hue City; 
Mr. Tran Viet Tan, Vietnamese ambassador to Myanmar; Mr. Doan 
Thao, deputy director general of the Physical and Sports General 
Department; and high-ranking officials of the Government of the 
SRV. 
  Prime Minister and Madame Vo Van Kiet and their entourage 
were accorded a warm welcome by the government and the people of 
Myanmar, reflecting the traditionally friendly relations between 
the two countries. The prime minister expressed great pleasure 
in having the opportunity to visit the Union of Myanmar and 
conveyed to the people of Myanmar the cordial greetings and 
wishes of the Vietnamese people. 
  During their stay in Myanmar, Prime Minister and Madame Vo 
Van Kiet and their entourage visited places of cultural and 
historical interests in Yangon [Rangoon] and Mandalay. They 
also had the opportunity to acquaint themselves with the 
progress and transformation taking place in Myanmar in the areas 
of agriculture and urban development. 
  The prime minister of the SRV paid a call on and had talks 
with Prime Minister Sr. Gen. Than Shwe. The two prime ministers 
had a friendly exchange of views on matters of mutual interests 
and current regional and international issues. The talks took 
place in an atmosphere of friendship and understanding. Present 
at the meeting with Prime Minister Sr. Gen. Than Shwe and Prime 
Minister Vo Van Kiet were: General Maung Aye, vice chairman of 
the State Law and Order Restoration Council [SLORC]; Lt. Gen. 
Tin Tun, deputy prime minister; Lt. Gen. Khin Nyunt, 
secretary-1 of the SLORC; Lt. Gen. Tin U, secretary-2 of the 
SLORC; U Ohn Gyaw, minister of foreign affairs; U Nyunt Swe, 
deputy minister of foreign affairs; U Aye, Myanmar ambassador to 
the SRV; Thura U Aung Htet, director general of the Protocol 
Department of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs; Mr. Nguyen Manh 
Cam, minister of foreign affairs; Mr. Tran Hoan, minister of 
culture and information; Mr. Nguyen Quang Ha, minister of 
forestry; Lt. Gen. Nguyen Thoi Bung, vice minister of national 
defense; Mr. Doan Manh Giao, vice chairman of the Government 
Office; Mr. Tran Van Tuyen, vice minister of commerce; Mr. Ngo 
Thi Doan, vice minister of agriculture and food industry; Mr. 
Nguyen Thuong Bang, vice minister of heavy industry; Mr. Do 
Quang Trung, chairman of the Vietnam Tourism Administration; 
Mr. Luu Van An, chairman of the People's Committee of Hue City; 
Mr. Tran Viet Tan, Vietnamese ambassador to Myanmar; and Mr. 
Doan Thao, deputy director general of the Physical and Sports 
General Department. 
  Lt. Gen. Tin Tun, deputy prime minister, and Lt. Gen. Khin 
Nyunt, secretary-1 of the SLORC, paid separate calls on Mr. Vo 
Van Kiet, prime minister of the SRV. The Myanmar side 
acquainted the visiting prime minister with the emerging 
constitutional, political, economic, and social changes taking 
place in the country and with the efforts to secure national 
reconciliation. The Myanmar side reaffirmed its independent and 
active foreign policy based on the five principles of peaceful 
coexistence and its active participation in the nonaligned 
movement. The Vietnamese side informed the Myanmar side of the 
comprehensive reform policy and the achievements recorded as 
well as the measures aimed at bringing the country into the new 
stage of development by gradually realizing industrialization 
and modernization. The Vietnamese side also reported on its 
independent sovereign, and opened and diversified foreign 
policy. The Myanmar side highly appreciated the reform policy 
and the achievements recorded by the Vietnamese people and 
wished the Vietnamese people many new successes in their noble 
cause. The two sides reaffirmed that the people of each country 
has the right to freely choose their own political, economic, 
and social system according to their needs, tradition, and 
culture and agreed to continue their cooperation in upholding 
these principles. Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet highly valued the 
efforts of the government and the people of Myanmar to achieve 
economic development and social progress and expressed his 
wishes for the success of these endeavors. 
  During the talks between the two foreign ministers, current 
political and economic development in the region were reviewed 
with emphasis on bilateral and regional cooperation. Separate 
talks at ministerial level of industrial, agricultural, 
forestry, commercial, cultural, physical and sports, and tourism 
affairs were also held. They agreed to promote cooperation in 
the respective fields between the two countries. The following 
agreements were signed after the talks: 
  1. agreement on the establishment of a joint commission 
for bilateral cooperation, 
  2. trade agreement and 
  3. agreement on tourism cooperation. 
  Lt. Gen. Nguyen Thoi Bung, vice minister of national 
defense, 
also called on Lt. Gen. Tin U, chief of the No.1 Special 
Operation Bureau and chief of staff of the Army. The two sides 
reaffirmed their desire to promote cooperation in the economic, 
environmental, cultural, tourism, agricultural, forestry, 
educational, and scientific field as well as in the fight 
against narcotic drugs. In the field of transport both sides 
agreed on specific steps to be taken to establish direct airline 
service between Myanmar and Vietnam at the earliest possible 
date. 
  The two prime ministers expressed their satisfaction on the 
successful visit of Mr. Vo Van Kiet, prime minister of the SRV, 
and his delegation to the Union of Myanmar, which significantly 
contributed to the strengthening of friendship and cooperation 
between the two countries. They welcomed the opportunity 
provided by the visit to renew personal contacts. Prime 
Minister of the SRV and Madame Vo Van Kiet conveyed their 
sincere thanks to Prime Minister and Madame Than Shwe for the 
warm and friendly hospitality provided to them and the entourage 
during the visit. The prime minister of the SRV and Madame Vo 
Van Kiet also extended an invitation to Prime Minister of the 
Union of Myanmar and Madame Than Shwe to visit the SRV at a 
mutual convenient time, and the invitation was accepted with 
pleasure. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

