<H4>    Ends Visit, Leaves Rangoon </H4>

<F P=102> BK1405151794 Rangoon Radio Burma in Burmese 1330 GMT 14 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1405151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rangoon Radio Burma </F>
<F P=105>  Burmese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mr. Vo Van Kiet, prime minister of the Socialist 
Republic of Vietnam [SRV], his wife, and entourage, who were 
paying a goodwill visit since 11 May at the invitation of Senior 
General Than Shwe, prime minister of the Union of Myanmar 
[Burma], left Yangon [Rangoon] by a special airplane this 
afternoon. 
  Prime Minister Mr. Vo Van Kiet and entourage were seen off 
at 
Yangon airport by Prime Minister Sr. Gen. Than Shwe and his 
wife; General Maung Aye, vice chairman of the State Law and 
Order Restoration Council [SLORC], and his wife; Lieutenant 
General Tin Tun, deputy prime minister, and his wife; Lt. Gen. 
Khin Nyunt, secretary-1 of the SLORC; Lt. Gen. Tin U, 
secretary-2 of the SLORC, and his wife; Lt. Gen. Myo Nyunt, 
minister of religious affairs; Brigadier General Myo Thant, 
minister of information; U Ohn Gyaw, minister of foreign 
affairs, and his wife; U Nyunt Swe, deputy minister of foreign 
affairs, and his wife; U Aye, Myanmar ambassador to the SRV, 
and his wife; Mr. Tran Viet Tan, ambassador of the SRV to the 
Union of Myanmar; high-ranking diplomats from the foreign 
missions; and members of the SRV Embassy. 
  The visiting Vietnamese Prime Minister Mr. Vo Van Kiet, his 
wife, and entourage visited the oil refinery in Syraim and Dagon 
University this morning. The visiting prime minister and 
entourage, accompanied by Deputy Foreign Minister U Nyunt Swe 
and party, arrived at the guest house of the Syriam Oil Refinery 
at 0820. They were welcomed by U Khin Maung Thein, minister of 
energy; U Tin Tun, deputy minister of energy; and responsible 
personnel. The visiting prime minister, his wife, and entourage 
then looked around the oil refinery and left the refinery at 
0930. Then they proceeded to the Dagon University in North 
Dagon Myothit. After visiting the campus, they left the 
university at 1130. 

</TEXT>

