<H3> <TI>   `About 100' Vietnamese Refugees Return Home </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `About 100' Vietnamese Refugees Return Home </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1405111294 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 13 
May 94 p 8 </F>

<F P=103> BK1405111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, Thurs. -- After five years in 
Malaysia, about 100 Vietnamese refugees, who were not accepted 
by any third country, left for Ho Chi Minh City today under the 
voluntary repatriation program. 
  So far, 3,054 Vietnamese illegal immigrants had voluntarily 
returned home since the programme began three years ago, leaving 
6,820 boat people at the Sungei Besi camp. 
  The returnees expressed enthusiasm about heading home as 
many 
felt the Vietnamese economy was brighter. Pham Phu Cong, 30, 
wants to return to his tailoring work. "My wife and I are happy 
to return as we are both in the tailoring line and want to start 
building a future for ourselves," said this father of one. 

</TEXT>

