<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ozawa Rejects Calls For SDP Return to Coalition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ozawa Rejects Calls For SDP Return to Coalition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605123694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1202 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605123694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 16 KYODO -- Political powerbroker Ichiro 
Ozawa called on the ruling coalition on Monday [16 May] to have 
confidence in its mission while rejecting proposals to permit 
the return of the maverick Social Democratic Party to the fold. 
  In a speech in Chiba, the Shinseito secretary general 
rejected any plans to do away with the intraparliamentary group 
"Kaishin (Innovation)" if it would entice the return of the 
second largest opposition party, which bolted from the coalition 
last month. 
  "The ruling party must have this kind of confidence. We must 
be able to have confidence in our ideals and answer the 
expectations of the people," said Ozawa, the acknowledged 
architect of the ruling minority coalition. 
  Earlier Monday, Takashi Yonezawa, secretary general of the 
Democratic Socialist Party, and Japan New Party executive Masao 
Matsuoka suggested the ruling coalition would be willing to 
withdraw plans for "Kaishin" if it would entice the return of 
the SDP. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata will formally inform SDP 
Chairman 
Tomiichi Murayama on Tuesday of the suggestion and urge the SDP 
to rejoin the coalition. 
  The SDP, however, has charged that there is still an 
"authoritarian character" to the current coalition and denied 
that there was any possibility of a return of the SDP to the 
ruling force. 
  The SDP withdrew from the ruling coalition only hours after 
it had helped elect Tsutomu Hata premier, upset by maneuvers by 
other coalition parties to form the new political alignment 
without the party. 
  Ozawa warned that in the event of general elections, the 
largest opposition Liberal Democratic Party would win by a 
landslide and that the "only other survivor would be Shinseito." 
  "We must not think only of the advantages before us and turn 
left or turn right. The socialists and Komeito were with us 
when we decided to proceed and we must think about achieving an 
historically great achievement," urged Ozawa. 
  Ozawa dismissed suggestions by murayama and new party 
Sakigake leader Masayoshi Takemura that the House of 
Representatives be dissolved for elections under the current 
electoral system. 
  "That is only the talk of people who do not have the right 
to 
decide on the dissolution. The cabinet will make that 
decision," said Ozawa. 

</TEXT>

