<H3> <TI>   To Submit No-Confidence Motion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    To Submit No-Confidence Motion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705033694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0326 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705033694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 17 KYODO -- The Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP) will submit a no-confidence motion against the cabinet of 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata after passage of the fiscal 1994 
budget through the Diet, a senior party official said Tuesday. 
  "Mr. Hata's role will be over once he passes the budget 
through the Diet," Yoshiro Mori, secretary general of the main 
opposition party, told a news conference. Mori blamed the 
cabinet of former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa for the long 
delay in the Diet budget debate, saying it put off the 
formulation of the budget from the usual year-end till this year 
to give top priority to political reform. "At the time, Mr. Hata 
was deputy prime minister," he said, indicating Hata should also 
be blamed for the delay in passage of the state budget, which is 
six weeks overdue. 
  Mori also said the LDP and the Social Democratic Party (SDP) 
[SDPJ], a member of Hosokawa's ruling coalition that collapsed 
in April, share a perception that Hata's minority government 
does not reflect the will of the Japanese people. 
  The SDPJ also sees the Hata cabinet as one to only handle 
the 
budget, Mori added. 
  The SDPJ walked out of the coalition shortly after Hata was 
elected premier in late April, in protest against the formation 
by other coalition partners of a new parliamentary group 
excluding the SDPJ. After the withdrawal of the SDPJ from the 
coalition, the LDP and the SDPJ, archrivals for decades, have 
moved to cooperate to put pressure on the Hata administration. 

</TEXT>

