<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Says Budget Delay Bad for Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Says Budget Delay Bad for Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705023894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0148 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705023894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 17 KYODO -- Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii expressed concern Tuesday [17 May] that the delay in 
getting the fiscal 1994 budget through parliament could put a 
damper on the economy, and stressed the need to limit the 
adverse effects. 
  "I can't deny that a long delay in (passing) the budget will 
affect the economy," Fujii told a regular news conference after 
a morning cabinet meeting. 
  Diet deliberations for the full 40 trillion yen budget for 
fiscal 1994 that started April 1 have been deadlocked because of 
political turmoil, and are to resume later Tuesday. 
  With about two months usually needed for a full budget to 
pass the Diet, however, the government decided last week to 
supplement for 40 days an already implemented 50-day 11 trillion 
yen stopgap budget that expires Friday. 
  "We must minimize the effects," Fujii added. But he did not 
spell out any concrete measures, saying the necessary public 
works and other outlays are included in the provisional budget. 
  The minister said, however, that fresh outlays in 
policy-related areas, such as infrastructure spending under the 
government's stimulus package, cannot be included in the planned 
supplementary budget, just as they could not be in the expiring 
stopgap budget. 
  Fujii said that he emphasized the importance for Japan to 
detail deregulatory steps in line with the March market-opening 
package during related ministerial talks held before the cabinet 
meeting. 
  Noting that Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata "strongly" called 
for 
political leadership at each ministry and agency, Fujii said the 
Finance Ministry will positively consider deregulation in 
financial services and insurance, which are particularly 
mentioned in the package. 
  But he said deregulation may cause some "pain" such as 
unemployment, and called for steadily implementation of the jobs 
and other welfare measures included in the full budget. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53070 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas095_a_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-095 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

