<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Sources Detail G-7 Summit Schedule </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Sources Detail G-7 Summit Schedule </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605154694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1458 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tokyo, May 16 KYODO -- The schedule for the July 
summit of the Group of Seven (G-7) economic powers in Naples has 
now taken shape, Foreign Ministry sources said Monday [16 May]. 
  The sources said that according to a provisional schedule 
worked out among the sherpas, or the personal representatives of 
the G-7 leaders, the summit leaders will begin their dialogue 
with a working dinner on the evening of July 8. 
  The leaders will consider economic issues in a formal 
session 
on July 9, a day which will also see the release of an economic 
declaration, as well as separate meetings among the foreign 
ministers and the finance ministers of the G-7. 
  Russian President Boris Yeltsin will make his first 
appearance at the Naples summit on the evening of July 9, when 
he attends a banquet. 
  On July 10, Yeltsin will join in political deliberations 
among the G-7 leaders on specific topics such as the former 
Yugoslavia, the Middle East and Eastern Europe. But the sources 
said there remain other topics to be discussed only among the 
G-7 countries themselves. 
  Later in the day, the G-7 countries will issue a chairman's 
summary and a political declaration. Along with Russia, the 
economic powers will also issue a political statement regarding 
the former Yugoslavia. 
  In the case of previous summits, the Kremlin leader only 
joined the G-7 leaders after their talks were already finished 
for a special "G-7-plus-one" session. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

