<F P=103> OW1605050594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 16 KYODO -- Two senior members of former 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's Japan New Party (JNP) 
proposed Monday [16 May] disbanding a four-party parliamentary 
group called Kaishin (Innovation), political sources said. 
  JNP legislators Satsuki Eda and Satoshi Arai filed the 
proposal with Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, the sources said. 
  Kaishin comprises 130 members in the House of 
Representatives 
of four coalition parties -- Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], 
JNP, the Democratic Socialist Party and Jiyuto (Liberals) -- 
plus five independents. 
  The April 25 establishment of Kaishin led to the departure 
of 
the Social Democratic Party [of Japan] (SDP) [SDPJ] from the 
ruling coalition, forcing Hata to form a minority government. 
  Kaishin ranks second in terms of strength in the lower house 
only after the main opposition party, the Liberal Democratic 
Party. 

</TEXT>

