<H3> <TI>   SDP, Sakigake Agree To Try To Reconcile Policy Gaps </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDP, Sakigake Agree To Try To Reconcile Policy Gaps </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605103294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0802 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 16 KYODO -- The Social Democratic Party 
(SDP) and new party Sakigake, which both quit the ruling 
coalition last month, agreed Monday [16 May] to initiate policy 
talks, officials of the two parties said. 
  The talks will cover Japan's response to North Korea's 
suspected nuclear arms program, tax system reform and rice 
prices, the officials said. 
  SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama and Sakigake leader Masayoshi 
Takemura reached the agreement in a meeting Monday, they said. 
  The SDP, the country's no. 2 opposition party, left the 
coalition late last month in protest over the establishment of a 
large parliamentary group that excluded it. 
  Sakigake earlier declared that it would not take cabinet 
posts but will cooperate with the cabinet of Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata for some time, keeping its distance from the 
coalition. 

