<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Legislators Launch New Policy Study Group in LDP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Legislators Launch New Policy Study Group in LDP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605132194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1036 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 16 KYODO -- Three senior Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) legislators, widely dubbed the "YKK 
Trio," on Monday [16 May] launched a new policy study group free 
from factional shackles. 
  The three vocal opposition politicians are former 
construction minister Taku Yamasaki, former chief cabinet 
secretary Koichi Kato and former posts and telecommunications 
minister Junichiro Koizumi. The name YKK trio is based on the 
initials of their family names. 
  "The group new century," headed by Kato, aims to "reform the 
party, create politics suitable for a new era and open up a new 
frontier for the future Japan," according to the group's 
constitution. 
  The group, which brought together over 60 LDP lawmakers, 
openly lashed out at Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party), the core 
ruling party headed by Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata but widely 
believed to be controlled by Ichiro Ozawa, the chief coalition 
strategist. 
  It blames Shinseito for inheriting the money-drenched 
politicking style of the LDP and for trying to manipulate the 
coalition government from behind the scenes. 
  The foundation of the new group within the LDP may 
accelerate 
moves toward a major reconfiguration of political parties in 
Japan, political sources said. 
  As the YKK trio are deemed as the critics of the current LDP 
leadership, led by President Yohei Kono, the group new century 
may also help proliferate an antileadership sentiment within the 
party, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

