<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Panels To Push for Taxation Reforms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Panels To Push for Taxation Reforms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605141394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1343 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 16 KYODO -- Three key government panels 
will form a joint conference to press the government to come up 
with an overall administrative reform plan that is vital to 
change the taxation system, sources close to the panels said 
Monday [16 May]. 
  The joint conference plan was agreed by the chairmen of the 
Tax Commission, the Economic Deliberation Council -- both 
advisory panels to the prime minister -- and the Fiscal System 
Council, an advisory body to the finance minister. 
  The conference, made up of 10 members sent by the panels, 
will study such issues as the scrapping and reorganization of 
government ministries and agencies and the further privatisation 
of public organizations. 
  It will present a concrete administrative reform plan to 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata by early June, the sources said. 
  They said panel leaders agreed that if they leave the 
long-proposed administrative reforms up to bureaucrats, the plan 
may lack substance. The leaders believe that the reforms should 
be carried out with the government taking the initiative, the 
sources added. 
  At present, Japan faces the needs to change its taxation 
system in order to implement income tax cuts designed to 
stimulate the flagging economy, the sources said. 
  Also, to cope with the rapid greying of the Japanese 
society, 
it is necessary to change the taxation system to secure funds to 
implement welfare programs for senior citizens, they added. 
  The panels have urged the government to promote 
across-the-board discussions between panels responsible for 
different fields, such as the economy and spending for social 
security and defense programs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

