<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fiscal '93 Public Works Investments `Highest' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fiscal '93 Public Works Investments `Highest' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605133194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1026 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 16 KYODO -- Public works projects 
started in fiscal 1993 totaled a record 19,758.5 billion yen, up 
7.8 percent from the previous year, the Construction Ministry 
reported Monday [16 May]. 
  The figure, which marks the ninth straight yearly increase, 
reflects a series of government moves to bolster public works as 
part of its economic stimulus packages. 
  The central government, public corporations and other state 
agencies placed orders for 4,860.7 billion yen worth of the 
total, up 8.1 percent. 
  Projects financed by autonomies and other local agencies 
accounted for the remaining 14,897.8 billion yen worth, a 7.7 
percent increase. 
  Both figures are the highest on record. 
  The ministry also said public works investments during March 
soared 67.8 percent from a year earlier to 2,353.5 billion yen. 

</TEXT>

