Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Reactor Tubes Reportedly Clogged With Rust </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Reactor Tubes Reportedly Clogged With Rust </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705003894 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 1000 GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1705003894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video; from the "NHK News 7" </F>
program] 
  [Text] Three years ago a tube clogged with rust broke in 
the No. 2 reactor of the Kansai Power Electric Company's Mihama 
nuclear power plant. An inhouse company report has found out 
that similar problems have occurred at six other nuclear plants. 
  In the incident three years ago, one of the tubes in a steam 
generator at the Mihama No. 2 reactor broke and leaked a large 
amount of primary cooling water, used to cool fuel in the 
reactor. Investigators later found one of the tubes had broken 
because an antivibration bar had not been properly installed. 
They said that foreign objects, including rust, had accumulated 
in a small gap between a tube and the bar, which supported the 
tubes. The tube eventually became fixed and could not withstand 
vibration. 
  NHK, which obtained a copy of the Kansai Electric Power 
Company's inhouse report, says after the accident investigators 
took samples from tubes at nine other pressurized water 
reactors, which are similar to the Mihama No. 2 reactor. They 
confirmed the tubes had become fixed because a gap between the 
tube and a bar in six of the reactors had become clogged. The 
report says that each of the 30 to 40 tubes that were checked at 
the Mihama No. 3 reactor and the No. 2 Ohi reactor, which are 
still in operation, were clogged with rust and dust and 
completely fixed. 
  Kansai Electric officials say that even though the tubes 
were 
clogged with dust, they would not break like the one at the 
Mihama No. 2 reactor unless it was triggered by an accident. 
They say they intend to replace the steam generators, together 
with the tubes, over the next four years. Antinuclear groups, 
however, including citizens' group, say that the reactors should 
be closed down immediately. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53098 </DOCNO>
