<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, U.S. To Discuss Global Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo, U.S. To Discuss Global Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705101494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0947 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 17 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
will hold a subcabinet-level meeting May 24 in Washington to 
discuss global cooperation, one of three areas in the bilateral 
trade "framework" talks, a senior Foreign Ministry official said 
Tuesday. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Sadayuki Hayashi and Sozaburo 
Okamatsu, vice trade minister for international affairs, will 
attend the meeting, the official said. Undersecretary of State 
Timothy Wirth will head the U.S. delegation. 
  The two countries are expected to discuss bilateral 
cooperation to battle illegal drugs, promote children's health, 
protect coral and observe geological processes, in addition to 
five fields that the two nations have been discussing under the 
framework talks, the official said. 
  Japan and the U.S. have been studying bilateral cooperation 
on the environment, technology, the development of human 
resources, population and AIDS. 
  Unlike the other two deadlocked areas of the framework talks 
-- macroeconomic and microeconomic areas -- the negotiations on 
global cooperation have seen some progress. 

</TEXT>

