<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Hopes Trade Talks Bring `Political Decision' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Hopes Trade Talks Bring `Political Decision' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705030094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0225 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705030094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 17 KYODO -- Japanese Trade Minister 
Eijiro Hata said Tuesday he hopes that subcabinet-level talks 
with the United States this week will pave the way for "a 
political decision" on resuming bilateral trade "framework" 
negotiations. 
  Speaking at a press conference, International Trade and 
Industry Minister Hata said the high-level talks will take place 
in Washington from Thursday. 
  Apart from the Washington talks, a subcabinet-level U.S. 
trade official may visit Tokyo in the near future, Hata said. 
  Hata said Sozaburo Okamatsu, vice international trade and 
industry minister for international affairs, and Sadayuki 
Hayashi, deputy foreign minister for economic affairs, will be 
sent to Washington for the talks, the duration of which has yet 
to be fixed. 
  Hata said they will not carry "specific answers" to three 
new 
U.S. proposals presented to Tokyo in April as conditions for 
resuming the negotiations on a new framework for bilateral trade. 
  The two Japanese officials will strive to "bridge the 
perception gap" between the two countries, Hata said. 
  The framework talks have been deadlocked since the February 
summit between then Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa 
and U.S. President Bill Clinton. The two sides have been at 
odds over the U.S.-proposed "objective criteria" for gauging 
American access to Japanese markets. 
  Turning to Russia's participation in political talks at the 
Naples summit of the Group of Seven (G-7) industrial countries 
in July, Hata said he personally supports the idea. 
  The global trend is moving toward accepting Russia as a new 
member of the G-7 club, he said. 

</TEXT>

