<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saito Says `Too Early' for Russia's G-7 Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saito Says `Too Early' for Russia's G-7 Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605094394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0859 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605094394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 16 KYODO -- Japan considers it to be 
"too early" for Russia to become a full member of the Group of 
Seven (G-7) economic powers, Vice Foreign Minister Kunihiko 
Saito said Monday [16 May]. 
  Saito told a press conference that Tokyo considers it too 
soon to include Russia in all discussions at G-7 summits because 
Japan does not yet have a peace treaty with Russia and because 
Russia still does not have the same status as other G-7 nations 
despite its reform efforts. 
  Other G-7 nations also share the same view, Saito said. 
  Saito said, however, the "sherpa" or personal 
representatives 
of G-7 leaders, are currently discussing ways to hold dialogue 
with Russia during the G-7 summit talks. 
  The prevailing view in the sherpa meeting is that it is 
necessary to include Russia, at least partially, in discussions 
on political topics to which Russia has some connections, such 
as the problems in the former Yugoslavia, Middle East and 
Eastern Europe, Saito said. 
  But the sherpas are negative on including Russia in 
discussions on economic matters because although Russia is 
making reform efforts, it is still a recipient of economic and 
financial aid, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

