<F P=103> BK1705061194 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City Radio Filipinas </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Fidel V. Ramos and [South] Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu, on Monday, reaffirmed their commitment to 
work for peace and stability, which they said is a key to 
progress and prosperity for all countries. The two also vowed 
to further strengthen bilateral relations between Manila and 
Seoul through constant dialogue and enhance economic cooperation. 
  In their 45-minute meeting, the president also reiterated to 
Minister Han the country's position on the North Korean issue 
which is for continued dialogue and search for peaceful 
approaches to the problem. The president told Minister Han, and 
I [newscaster] quote, we have taken a very strong supportive 
position, vis-a-vis the North Korean issue, [word indistinct] 
our region we are one of the most anti-communist here, unquote. 
  As a member of the executive board of the International 
Atomic Energy Agency, the Philippines will support any 
initiative on the part of South Korea to diffuse tension between 
Seoul and Pyongyang. The president said, and I quote, again we 
are very much concerned that's why we are pushing for an 
encouraging maximum possible diplomatic and political courses of 
action that can bring about better convictions for peace and 
stability in the region, unquote. 
  The president also thanked the Korean Government for the 
training and skills upgrading it offered to the Filipino workers 
there. Also present during the meeting were Korean Ambassador 
Chang-su Yi, Foreign Affairs Director General for Asia-Pacific 
(Yu Byung Woo) and Foreign Affairs Director for Southeast Asia 
and Pacific Division (Moon Tai Yang). They were accompanied to 
Malacanang by Foreign Affairs Secretary Roberto Romulo. 

</TEXT>

