<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Reviews Vo Van Kiet Visit to Burma </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Reviews Vo Van Kiet Visit to Burma </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1605154094 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam in English 1000 GMT 16 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1605154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Station commentary] </F>
  [Text] Vietnam and Myanmar [Burma] are two countries in 
Southeast Asia which have traditional relations. The late 
President of Vietnam Ho Chi Minh visited Myanmar 35 years ago, 
and that visit was a turning point in the road of mutual 
understanding between the two nations. 
  Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet's visit also left a deep 
impression on the Myanmar people. Despite the changing weather, 
thousands of people in their colorful traditional costumes, 
lined up along the road leading to the center of Rangoon to 
welcome Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet and his party. On the very 
first day of his visit, all newspapers in Myanmar frontpaged 
portrait and biography of Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet. They also 
carried editorials praising relations between the two countries. 
  Various meetings among state leaders of the two countries 
took place in the atmosphere of mutual understanding. Future 
economic and trade cooperation between Vietnam and Myanmar was 
an important topic at the talks. An agreement on trade was 
signed in 1976, but trade turnover was very modest, mainly in 
exchange of consumer goods and family facilities. Therefore, 
this time both Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet and his 
Myanmar counterpart Than Shwe expressed the determination to 
further strengthen cooperative relations between the two 
countries. 
  Prime Minister Than Shwe said that he has been following, 
with keen interest, the successful process of renovation in 
Vietnam. He said that there was no obstacle for Myanmar to 
develop its relations with Vietnam. 
  Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet said: Vietnam always attaches 
great importance to the development of more bilateral 
cooperation with Myanmar. An agreement on trade, tourism 
cooperation and the establishment of a joint commission of 
bilateral cooperation was signed during the visit. It is the 
concrete manifestation of the two countries' determination. 
  Myanmar is now in its process of renovation. Hence, Vietnam 
and Myanmar share much in common. The existing fine relations 
between Vietnam and Myanmar and the outcome of the visit by 
Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet will usher in a new stage of 
relations and cooperation between the two countries. This was 
assessed by the foreign ministers of Vietnam and Myanmar. And 
now the two nations are trying their best to make their 
cooperation more effective and fruitful. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

