<H3> <TI>   Evans Says Military Aid to Cambodia `Legitimate' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Evans Says Military Aid to Cambodia `Legitimate' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1305110594 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1305110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Australia's foreign minister, Gareth Evans, says it 
is wholly legitimate for the Cambodian Government to seek 
military assistance from the international community. He was 
commenting on a warning from Thailand's security chief for 
Australia not to give military aid, saying it would only 
escalate the conflict between the Cambodian Government and the 
Khmer Rouge. 
  In a statement issued in Canberra, Senator Evans said 
Australia is giving serious consideration to the Cambodian 
Government's request for military assistance. He said Australia 
would consult with and take into account the views of other 
countries, including Thailand. 
  The foreign minister said it is in line with the Paris peace 
accord for the elected Cambodian Government to seek aid from the 
international community in order to maintain the country's 
sovereignty and territorial integrity. But Senator Evans also 
made it clear that it would be helpful if countries which 
committed themselves to the Cambodian peace process were to help 
the Armed Forces of the legitimate government. 

</TEXT>

