<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Peace Parade' Speaker Condemns `Secret Deal' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Peace Parade' Speaker Condemns `Secret Deal' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1305204694 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 13 May 94 
Evening Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1305204694 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This year's annual "May 15 Peace Parade" (sponsored 
by the Okinawa Peace Movement Center) kicked off at 0930 (local 
time) on 13 May at three different locations in Okinawa, 
including the Peace Prayer Park in Itoman city and the Nago city 
office. The parade has traditionally been held to appeal for 
the establishment of peace in Okinawa through the removal of 
U.S. military bases. Participants in the parade will continue 
marching until they reach their destination, which is a 
beachside park in Kadena Township where a general rally is to be 
held on 15 May. The event has been held 16 times in the past. 
  A total of about 2,000 participants, including about 800 
from 
other prefectures, are expected to participate in the parade. 
About 5,000 participants are expected to gather at the general 
rally. A ceremony was held at the Peace Prayer Park to mark the 
beginning of the parade for the group of marchers who plan to 
take the southern route starting in Itoman city. There were 
about 400 participants at the ceremony. 
  In a speech greeting the participants, Zenshun Arakaki, 
chairman of the Peace Movement Center, said: "The existence of a 
`secret deal between the Japanese and U.S. Governments for 
bringing nuclear weapons to Okinawa' has been revealed. We have 
learned that the three nonnuclear principles were only a hoax. 
Moreover, the ruling coalition government is planning to enact 
emergency legislation by taking advantage of the issue of the 
DPRK's (North Korea) suspected nuclear weapons development 
program. What we really need is a nuclear inspection of U.S. 
military bases on Okinawa." Arakaki encouraged the marchers by 
saying, "Let us complete our parade." 
  In their speeches, local representatives of various parties 
one after the other stressed the seriousness of the issue of the 
secret deal regarding bringing nuclear weapons to Okinawa. 
Representatives from other prefectures also said: "For Okinawa, 
the postwar period is not yet over. The reversion of Okinawa to 
Japan was a fraud." 

</TEXT>

