<H3> <TI>   Ouchi Proposes Nonpartisan Caretaker Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ouchi Proposes Nonpartisan Caretaker Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1805125594 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 May 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1805125594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It was disclosed on 17 May that Democratic Socialist 
Party Chairman Keigo Ouchi said at a meeting held with senior 
members of a religious group in Tokyo in the evening of 16 May 
that "we would like to form a nonpartisan caretaker government 
after approval of the fiscal 1994 budget and resignation of the 
cabinet en bloc." He made this remark as a countermeasure to 
deal with the situation if no-confidence motion is submitted 
against the Hata cabinet. According to a source concerned, 
Ouchi took into consideration the possibility of including the 
Liberal Democratic Party in forming the next coalition 
government. Ouchi reportedly said: "We need to immediately 
approve the bill for redrawing electoral districts for the House 
of Representatives. After that, we can dissolve the Diet and 
hold a general election in either November or December." 

</TEXT>

